:"1380–1450","1393–1450":"1393–1450","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1345–1388":"1345–1388","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1364":"1364","1474":"1474","1374":"1374","1450":"1450","1409":"1409","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","Conwy, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Conwy, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Waveney, Suffolk, England":"Waveney, Suffolk, England","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jernegan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk): of uncertain origin. Reaney believes it to be of Breton origin, probably identical with the Old Breton personal name <i>Iarnuuocon</i> ‘iron famous’, taken to East Anglia by Bretons at the time of the Norman Conquest. Compare   Journigan  .","History: Thomas Jernigan was granted land at Somerton, VA, in 1668. Many of his descendants were sea captains. His son, also called Thomas, settled on Martha's Vineyard, MA, in 1712."],"variants":[{"name":"Jarnigan","meanings":["English: variant of   Jernigan  ."]},{"name":"Jarnagin","meanings":["English: variant of   Jernigan  ."]},{"name":"Journigan","meanings":["Altered form of   Jernigan  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Jernegan was born in 1380, in Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England, his father, John Shelton Jernegan III, was 16 and his mother, Margaret Vis de Lou, was 36. He married Joan Appleyard in 1409, in Somerleyton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1450, in Caernarfonshire, Wales, at the age of 70, and was buried in Somerleyton, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1393–1450":"1393–1450","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1345–1388":"1345–1388","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1364":"1364","1474":"1474","1374":"1374","1450":"1450","1409":"1409","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","Conwy, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Conwy, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Waveney, Suffolk, England":"Waveney, Suffolk, England","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1393–1450":"1393–1450","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1345–1388":"1345–1388","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1364":"1364","1474":"1474","1374":"1374","1450":"1450","1409":"1409","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1380":"1380","Conwy, Caernarfons